<img src=http://bargainshoppercentral.com/saga/Jebbarsig.jpg></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/umaladominus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Maladominus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Ak'Anon Sex Symbol</span><br>  Posts: 809<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/30/02 5:40:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2620.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Parsed fantasy languages, a dream</span><hr size=1> Languages are not truly RP unless.... Verant went out of their way to parse each and every language. <br>
<br>
Let me explain: <br>
<br>
Example of Maladominus and Xethux conversing with each other, and assuming that both are not fluent in understanding each other's native tongues ---- <br>
<br>
Xethux says &quot;Well well if it isn't the little hairy-mammal again! And what brings you to Kunark, hairy-mammal pirate man?&quot;<br>
<br>
[if Maladominus does not understand Lizardman, thus hears]<br>
<br>
Xethux says, in Lizardman, &quot;Hiss viss kli ik the lisssle hairy-mammal shinnnsa! Inss what bringsss ish snishka ni Kunark, ikskhra-vensh pirate man?&quot;<br>
<br>
Maladominus responds to Xethux -- <br>
<br>
Maladominus says &quot;Arrrr! Avast ya rotten lizard-man tallard, dontcha be hoistin yer silly Ruler of the Galaxy nonsense on me!&quot;<br>
<br>
Xethux only hears: <br>
<br>
Maladominus says, in Gnomish, &quot;Arrrr! Dinks yar cogboddle lizard-bik mugwumpus, nilistatin be oogbodle nik Tinkity nog Tockity nonsense in oort!&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
This is how languages should really work... they should be parsed almost like riddles and foreign heiroglyphics, a bunch of foreigner words and syntax that you can ALMOST make out.... but not quite. The better your comprehension of the language, the more accurare your translation becomes. <br>
<br>
It adds dimension and depth to speaking and hearing languages.  It also adds a higher touch of role playing and intrigue, almost like &quot;Hey, gnomish sure is a creepy sounding language! But at least it's not as gutteral as Ogrish!&quot; <br>
<br>
I have played prior RPGs that did exactly this. They parsed the foreign language.  <br>
<br>
So Orcish sounds like Orcish. <br>
<br>
And Elvish sounds very Elvish, a song-like smooth flowing language of the elves. <br>
<br>
And Barbarian tongues actually sounded harsh and barbaric.<br>
<br>
If I were in charge of producing say.... EverQuest III, this would be a feature in the game.  I'm an advocate for detail  *shrugs*<br>
<br>
